nkrijk"},"en":{"1360–1414":"1360–1414","1314–1372":"1314–1372","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1300–1362":"1300–1362","1305–1372":"1305–1372","Abt 1362":"about 1362","1305":"1305","1414":"1414","1314":"1314","about 1380":"about 1380","1300":"1300","1474":"1474","1362":"1362","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Knodishall, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Kingsley, Cheshire, England":"Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gerard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Camille, Jean-Pierre, Murielle, Emile, Pascal, Pierre, Agathe, Alain, Aldes, Antoine, Armand.","French (<b>Gérard</b>), Walloon (mainly <b>Gérard</b>), and English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Gérard</i>, <i>Gerard</i> (from Old French <i>Gerart</i>, <i>Girart</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. As a surname of French origin it is also found in Haiti. Compare   Garrard   and also French   Guerard  , English   Garard  ,   Gerrard  , and   Jarrard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Enzo, Gaspare, Luigi, Rocco, Antonio, Canio, Carmine, Filippo, Francesco, Giovanni, Libero.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  ). This surname is also found in southern France.","German and French (mainly Nord): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name German   Gerhard  , French <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ), using the genitive of the Latinized form <i>Gerardus</i>."]},{"name":"Garrison","meanings":["English: from a shortened form of Middle English <i>Gerardson</i>, a patronymic from the personal name   Gerard   + <i>son</i>, or an Anglicized form of its Dutch cognate   Gerritsen  . The English surname is probably in most cases of Flemish or Dutch origin. It was brought to Britain by immigrants from the Low Countries, especially in the 15th and 16th centuries.","Americanized form of Jewish   Gerson   (see   Gershon  ).","Americanized form of Dutch   Gerritsen  ."]},{"name":"Garrard","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Gerard  .","Altered form of French <b>Gérard</b> (see   Gerard  ).","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Geenen","meanings":["Dutch, Flemish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Geen</i>, a pet form of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Gerardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Alberto, Alfredo, Aurelio, Carlos, Jesus, Juan, Norberto, Ramon, Tomas, Ana.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Dino, Enrico, Marco, Marco Antonio.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  )."]},{"name":"Gerald","meanings":["English (of Norman origin); French (<b>Gérald</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerald</i>, <i>Girald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ and <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’. It was introduced to Britain by the Normans and was fairly common, but less so than   Gerard  , with which it was early confused. In France the much more common variants of this surname are <b>Géraud</b> and   Giraud  ."]},{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["English: variant of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Geron","meanings":["French (<b>Géron</b>): from the personal name <i>Gero</i>, <i>Gerone</i>, a short form of ancient Germanic names formed with the element <i>gār, gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, as for example <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ).","Altered form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  ).","English (Lancashire): of Norman origin, from the personal name <i>Geron</i> of ancient Germanic origin, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Gherardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Silvio, Alessandro, Angelo, Antonio, Donato, Egidio, Ennio, Enzo, Gildo, Lucio, Luigi, Primo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Gherardo</i>, one of themany Italian equivalents of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Garard","meanings":["English (London and Buckinghamshire): variant of   Gerard  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Maud Gerard was born in 1360, in Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William FitzWilliam Gerard, was 61 and her mother, Jane De Bryan, was 55. She married John Layton. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1414, in Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1360–1414":"1360–1414","1314–1372":"1314–1372","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1300–1362":"1300–1362","1305–1372":"1305–1372","Abt 1362":"umbes 1362","1305":"1305","1414":"1414","1314":"1314","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1300":"1300","1474":"1474","1362":"1362","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Knodishall, Suffolk, England":"Knodishall with Buxlow, Suffolk, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kingsley, Cheshire, England":"Kingsley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1360–1414":"1360–1414","1314–1372":"1314–1372","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1380–1474":"1380–1474","1300–1362":"1300–1362","1305–1372":"1305–1372","Abt 1362":"no